{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image= Avishay.braverman.png |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1948|1|15|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]] |Year of Aliyah = |death_date = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 2006|17]], [[Israeli legislative election, 2009|18]], [[Israeli legislative election, 2013|19]] |party1 = [[Israeli Labor Party|Labor Party]] |partyyears1 = 2006–2015 |minister1 = [[Minorities Minister of Israel|Minister of Minorities]] |ministeryears1 = 2009–2011 |}}
'''Avishay Braverman''' ({{lang-he-n|אבישי ברוורמן}}, born 15 January 1948) is an [[Israel]]i economist and politician. A former president of the [[Ben-Gurion University of the Negev]], he served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for the [[Israeli Labor Party|Labor Party]] between 2006 and 2015, and as [[Minorities Minister of Israel|Minister of Minority Affairs]] between 2009 and 2011.
==Biography== Braverman studied statistics and economics at [[Tel Aviv University]] and received his PhD in economics from [[Stanford University]] in the [[United States]]. After serving for fourteen years as a senior official in the [[World Bank]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], specializing in economic development with an emphasis on [[social justice]], Braverman returned to Israel to become president of the Ben-Gurion University of the Negev for the next sixteen years. He was well regarded in this position and received an award from the city of [[Be'er Sheva]] for his work.
In November 2005, Braverman announced his intention to become involved in politics. Despite rumors that he would join [[Kadima]], in a move viewed as surprising, he ended up joining [[Israeli Labor Party|Labor Party]].<ref>[https://www.jpost.com/Israel/Braverman-joins-Labor-not-Kadima Braverman joins Labor, not Kadima] The Jerusalem Post, 24 November 2005</ref> He was elected to the Knesset in the [[Israeli legislative election, 2006|2006 elections]]. Within the party, he was initially associated with [[Amir Peretz]] and later with [[Ami Ayalon]].
Prior to the [[Israeli legislative election, 2009|2009 elections]] he won fourth place in the [[Primary election|party's primaries]], retaining his seat in the subsequent election. Braverman opposed the decision of the Labor Party to enter the [[Benjamin Netanyahu|Netanyahu]] government in March 2009, but shortly afterwards it was announced that he would be entering the government as Minister without Portfolio, focusing on Minority Affairs, later transformed into the [[Minorities Minister of Israel|Minister of Minority Affairs]].<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1075341.html Netanyahu sworn in as Israel's prime minister] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102083155/http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1075341.html |date=January 2, 2010 }} Haaretz, 1 April 2009</ref> He resigned from the cabinet after [[Ehud Barak]] left the Labor Party to establish [[Independence (Israeli political party)|Independence]] in January 2011.<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4014839,00.html Labor ministers quit gov't after split] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917133600/http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0%2C7340%2CL-4014839%2C00.html |date=September 17, 2016 }} Ynetnews, 17 January 2011</ref> He was re-elected to the Knesset in [[Israeli legislative election, 2013|2013]].
In December 2014 Braverman announced that he would not run in the [[Israeli legislative election, 2015|2015 elections]], stating that he felt he had done all he could as a Knesset member.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-Elections/Labor-MK-Avishay-Braverman-announces-he-wont-run-in-March-elections-384697 Labor MK Avishay Braverman announces he won't run in March elections] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304062648/http://www.jpost.com/Israel-Elections/Labor-MK-Avishay-Braverman-announces-he-wont-run-in-March-elections-384697 |date=March 4, 2016 }} The Jerusalem Post, 15 December 2014</ref>
