{{BLP primary sources|date=February 2009}} '''James A. Paul''' (born June 10, 1941) is a writer and non-profit executive who has worked throughout his career in the field of [[international relations]] and global policy.
Paul was born in New York City and graduated from [[Phillips Exeter Academy]] and earned a B.A. from [[Harvard College]] in 1963. He went on to earn an M.A. at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and a Ph.D. from [[New York University]] in 1975 with a specialty in comparative politics.
Between 1972 and 1976, Paul was Lecturer and then Assistant Professor of Political Science at [[Empire State College]] of the [[State University of New York]]. In 1976, he took a position with the [[Middle East Research and Information Project]] (MERIP) as a member of the Editorial Committee of the magazine ''MERIP Reports'' (later ''[[Middle East Report]]''). Paul later served on the MERIP Board and was appointed Executive Director of the organization in 1985. From 1989–1993, he worked full-time as a free-lance writer and consultant. Since 1993 he has served as founding Executive Director of [[Global Policy Forum]], an organization that monitors policy-making at the [[United Nations]].
Paul has served on many boards and committees. He was Chair of the Board of Trustees of the World Fellowship Center, member of the Committee for an Exploratory Study of Graduate Education in Political Science of the [[American Political Science Association]] and member of the Editorial Committee of Peuples Méditerranéens. For many years, he has been involved in New York City housing issues as a leader of the Trinity House Tenants’ Association.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/10/nyregion/10trinity.html?ref=todayspaper The New York Times: December 10, 2007]</ref> From 1995–1999, Paul was the representative of the Paris-based [[International Federation of Human Rights]] at UN headquarters. Since 1995, he has frequently served as Chair of the NGO Working Group on the [[Security Council]] and he is currently Vice-Chair of the group. He is also Convener of the NGO Working Group on Food and Hunger and serves as board Chair of the Repast Baroque Ensemble.<ref>[http://www.repastbaroque.org/ REPAST BAROQUE ENSEMBLE]</ref> His honors include the World Hunger Media Award and a "Peacemaker" award by the [[Nuclear Age Peace Foundation]].
Paul gives many interviews to the print and broadcast media.<ref>[http://ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=44590 IPS Inter Press Service: Nov 5 2008], [http://www.globalissues.org/news/2009/02/09/573 Global Issues: February 09, 2009]</ref> He has authored well over a hundred articles and reviews in academic journals, magazines and other print media, and he has written dozens of policy papers for Global Policy Forum. He has spoken and written extensively on [[Iraq]],<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/15/opinion/15herbert.html?_r=2 The New York Times: September 15, 2007]</ref> [[oil]],<ref>[http://www.democracynow.org/2004/6/3/black_gold_controlling_global_oil_from Democracy Now! June 3, 2004]</ref> the [[UN Security Council]], UN finance, and the hunger/food crisis.<ref>[http://www.nuso.org/upload/fes_pub/wahlberg.pdf A New Era of World Hunger? [[Friedrich Ebert Foundation]], August 2008]</ref> He has served as an editor of the ''[[Oxford Companion]] to Politics of the World'' (1993, second edition 2001). He wrote ''Syria Unmasked'' <ref>[http://www.danielpipes.org/530/syria-unmasked-the-suppression-of-human-rights-by-the-asad Daniel Pipes: Fall 1991]</ref> (1991) and ''Humanity Comes of Age'' <ref>http://www.articlearchives.com/trade-development/economic-development-emerging-markets/1488115-1.html offline</ref> (1994).
==Selected publications== * With Katarina Wahlberg: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/socecon/hunger/general/2008/07paulwahlberg.pdf A New Era of World Hunger? – The Global Food Crisis Analyzed] (2008) * With Celine Nahory: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/security/reform/2005/0713theses.htm Towards a Democratic Reform of the UN Security Council] (2005) * [http://www.globalpolicy.org/security/ngowkgrp/gpfpaper.htm NGOs and the Security Council] (2004) * With Marianna Quenemoen: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/socecon/crisis/2003/07gpfdollar.htm The Fall of the Dollar] (2003) * With John Rempel, Richard Moran, et al.: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/security/sanction/iraq1/2002/paper.htm Iraq Sanctions: Humanitarian Implications and Options for the Future] (2002) * With Katarina Wahlberg: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/socecon/glotax/general/glotaxpaper.htm Global Taxes for Global Priorities] (2002) * [http://www.globalpolicy.org/ngos/analysis/anal00.htm NGOs and Global Policy-Making] (2000) * [http://www.globalpolicy.org/nations/micro.htm Small States and Territories] (2000) * With Jason Garred: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/socecon/ffd/2000papr.htm Making Corporations Accountable] (2000) * With Jens Martens: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/socecon/ffd/paul.htmThe Coffers are not Empty: financing for sustainable development and the role of the United Nations] (1998) * [http://www.globalpolicy.org/nations/natstats.htm Nations and States] (1996) * With Susanne Paul: [http://www.globalpolicy.org/socecon/bwi-wto/pensions.htm The World Bank and the Attack on Pensions in the Global South] (1994)
