'''Vital Hébert''' (ca 1808 &ndash; 1867)<ref name="craig"/> was a landowner and political figure in [[New Brunswick]]. He represented Victoria in the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] from 1866 to 1867. He was the first French-speaking member to represent the county in the assembly.<ref name="craig">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UG1zVNtVy4wC&pg=PA62 |title=Backwoods consumers and homespun capitalists: the rise of a market culture in eastern Canada |last=Craig |first=Beatrice |page=62 |ISBN=0-8020-9317-5 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |year=2009}}</ref>
He was the son of Simon "Simonet" Hébert. Hébert served as deputy treasurer for [[Victoria County, New Brunswick|Victoria County]] in 1865. He died in office at the age of 59.<ref name="craig"/>
